} command) are ignored.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} !BREAK directive}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} .BREAK}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Directives:BREAK}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} !BREAK;!WHILE;loop}} !BREAK
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb directive}{\v Directives} lets you abort out of the most inner currently executing {\uldb while loop}{\v .WHILE}, in a {\uldb macro}{\v MacroLanguage}
. It is often used to abort processing for error conditions. For example:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 ; Read in files and substitute "beginning" with "beginning"
\par set %filename #list
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 !while &not &seq %filename "<end>"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 !force    find-file %filename
\par     !if &seq $status FALSE
\par         write-message "[File read error]"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880         {\b !break}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     !endif
\par     beginning-of-file
\par     replace-string "beginning" "beginning"
\par     save-file
\par     set %filename #list
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 !endwhile
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} !ENDM directive}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} .ENDM}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Directives:endm}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} !ENDM;macro}} !ENDM
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb directive}{\v Directives} is used to terminate a macro{\v MacroLanguage} being stored. For example:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 ; Read in a file in view mode, and make the window red
\par store-procedure get-red-viewed-file
\par     view-file @"File to view: "
\par     add-mode "red"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 {\b !endm}
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Related commands:
\par \pard\plain \s11\li360\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\uldb store-procedure}{\v store_procedure}
\par \pard \s11\li360\sa120\tx2880 {\uldb store-macro}{\v store_macro}.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} !FORCE directive}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} .FORCE}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Directives:force}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} !FORCE;error}} !FORCE
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 When MicroEMACS executes a {\uldb macro}{\v MacroLanguage}, if any command fails, the macro is terminated at that point. If a line is preceded by a !FORCE {\uldb directive}{\v Directives}
, execution continues whether the command succeeds or not.
\par This is often used together with the {\uldb $status}{\v _status} variable to test if a command succeeded. For example:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 set %seekstring @"String to Find: "
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 {\b !force} search-forward %seekstring
\par !if {\b $status}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     print "Your string is Found"
\par !else
\par     print "No such string!"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 {\f11 !endif
\par }\pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} !GOTO directive}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} .GOTO}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Directives:goto}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} !GOTO;!WHILE;loop}} !GOTO
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 The flow of execution within a MicroEMACS {\uldb macro}{\v MacroLan}{\v guage} can be controlled using the !GOTO {\uldb directive}{\v Directives}
. It takes a label as argument. A label consists of a line starting with an asterisk "*" and then an alphanumeric label. Only labels in the currently executing macro can be jumped to, and trying to jump to a non-existing label terminates execution of a ma
cro. For example:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 ; Create a block of DATA statements for a BASIC program
\par insert-string "1000 DATA "
\par set %linenum 1000
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 {\b *nxtin}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 update-screen    ;make sure we see the changes
\par set %data @@"Next number: "
\par !if &equal %data 0
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     {\b !goto} finish
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 !endif
\par !if &greater $curcol 60
\par     2 delete-previous-character
\par     newline
\par     set %linenum &add %linenum 10
\par     insert-string &cat %linenum " DATA "
\par !endif
\par insert-string &cat %data ", "
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 {\b !goto} nxtin
\par {\b *finish}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 2 delete-previous-character
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 newline
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Note that loops constructed with {\uldb !WHILE}{\v .WHILE} are usually more efficient than those constructed purely by !GOTOs.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} !IF, !ELSE and !ENDIF directives}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain 
\f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} .IF}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Directives:if}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} !IF;!ELSE;!ENDIF}} !IF, !ELSE and !ENDIF
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 The !IF {\uldb directive}{\v Directives} allows for conditional execution within a {\uldb macro}{\v MacroLanguage}.
\par Lines following the !IF directive, until the corresponding !ELSE or !ENDIF, are executed only if the expression within the !IF line {\uldb evaluates}{\v Arguments}
 to a TRUE value. Lines following an !ELSE directive, until the corresponding !ENDIF, are executed only if the expression within the corresponding !IF line did not evaluate to a TRUE value.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 For example, the following macro creates the portion of a text file automatically:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 {\b !if} &sequal %curplace "timespace vortex"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     insert-string "First, rematerialize~n"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 {\b !endif}
\par {\b !if} &sequal %planet "earth"    ;If we have landed on earth...
\par     {\b !if} &sequal %time "late 20th century"    ;and we are then
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880         write-message "Contact U.N.I.T."
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     {\b !else}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880         insert-string "Investigate the situation....~n"
\par         insert-string "(SAY 'stay here Sarah)~n"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     {\b !endif}
\par {\b !else}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     set %conditions @"Atmosphere conditions outside? "
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     {\b !if} &sequal %conditions "safe"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880         insert-string &cat "Go outside......" "~n"
\par         insert-string "lock the door~n"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     {\b !else}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880         insert-string "Dematerialize..try somewhen else"
\par         newline
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     {\b !endif}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 {\b !endif}
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} !RETURN directive}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} .RETURN}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Directives:return}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} !RETURN}} !RETURN
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb directive}{\v Directives} causes the current {\uldb macro}{\v MacroLanguage} to exit, either returning to the caller (if any) or to interactive mode. For example:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 ; Check the display type and set %wintyp
\par !if &sequal $sres "MSWIN"
\par     set %wintyp 1
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     {\b !return}
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 !endif
\par set %wintyp 0
\par write-message "You are not running under MS-Windows!"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 {\b !return}
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} !WHILE and !ENDWHILE directives}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain 
\f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} .WHILE}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Directives:while}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote 
\pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} !WHILE;!ENDWHILE;loop;!BREAK}} !WHILE and !ENDWHILE
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This pair of {\uldb directives}{\v Directives} facilitates repetitive execution within a {\uldb macro}{\v MacroLanguage}. If a group of statements needs to be executed while a certain expression {\uldb evaluates}{
\v Arguments} to TRUE, enclose them with a while loop. For example:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 {\b !while} &less $curcol 70
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880     insert-string &cat &cat "[" #stuff "]"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 {\b !endwhile
\par }\pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 While loops may be nested and can contain and be the targets of {\uldb !GOTOs}{\v .GOTO} with no ill effects.  Using a while loop to enclose a repeated task will run much faster than the corresponding constr
uct using {\uldb !IFs}{\v .IF}.
\par \pard\plain \s253\sa240\tx2880 \b\f2\cf2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Arguments}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Arguments}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} MacroLanguage:030}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} argument;evaluate;expression;}} Arguments
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 In the MicroEMACS {\uldb macro language}{\v MacroLanguage}, {\uldb commands}{\v Commands} and {\uldb functions}{\v Functions}
 often require arguments. There are three types of arguments and they are automatically converted to the proper type when used:
\par \pard\plain \s2\fi-2520\li2880\sa120\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\b Numerical}\tab An ASCII string of digits which is interpreted as a numeric value. Any string which does not start with a digit or a minus sign "{\b -}" will be considered zero.
\par \pard \s2\fi-2520\li2880\sa120\tx2880 {\b String}\tab An arbitrary string of characters. Strings are limited to 128 characters in length. 
\par \pard \s2\fi-2520\li2880\sa120\tx2880 {\b Boolean}\tab 
A logical value consisting of the string "TRUE" or "FALSE". Numeric strings will also evaluate to "FALSE" if they are equal to zero, and "TRUE" if they are non-zero. Arbitrary text strings will be considered equivalent "FALSE".
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 While arguments usually follow the command or function that uses them, a single numerical argument can also be placed in front of a command, producing an effect similar to the {\uldb numeric arguments}{\v 
NumericArguments} used in interactive mode.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 If a command needs more arguments than have be supplied on the line, the command fails.
\par \pard\plain \s253\sa240\tx2880 \b\f2\cf2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Constants}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Constants}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} MacroLanguage:040}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} constants;macro}} Constants
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Wherever {\uldb macro language}{\v MacroLanguage} statements need to have {\uldb arguments}{\v Arguments}
, it is legal to place constants. A constant is a double quote character, followed by a string of characters, and terminated by another double quote character.
\par The double quotes around constants are not needed if the constant contains no white space and it also does not happen to meet the rules for any other MicroEMACS {\uldb commands}{\v Commands}, {\uldb directives}{\v Directiv}{\v es}, {\uldb variables}{\v 
Variables}, or {\uldb functions}{\v Functions}. This is very practical for numeric constants.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 To represent various special characters within a constant, the tilde "~" character is used. The character following the tilde is interpreted according to the following table:
\par \pard\plain \s7\fi-1080\li1440\sa120\tx1440\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\b Sequence}\tab {\b Meaning}
\par \pard \s7\fi-1080\li1440\sa120\tx1440\tx2880 ~"\tab double quote
\par ~~\tab tilde
\par \pard \s7\fi-1080\li1440\sa120\tx1440\tx2880 ~b\tab backspace ({\ul ^H}{\v Keystroke})
\par ~f\tab formfeed ({\ul ^L}{\v Keystroke})
\par ~l\tab linefeed ({\ul ^J}{\v Keystroke})
\par \pard \s7\fi-1080\li1440\sa120\tx1440\tx2880 ~n\tab newline
\par \pard \s7\fi-1080\li1440\sa120\tx1440\tx2880 ~r\tab carriage return ({\ul ^M}{\v Keystroke})
\par ~t\tab tab ({\ul ^I}{\v Keystroke})
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Any character not in the above table which follows a tilde will be passed unmodified. This action is similar to the {\uldb quote-character}{\v quote_character} ({\ul ^Q}{\v Keystroke}
) command available from the keyboard.
\par MicroEMACS may use different characters for line terminators on different computers. The "{\b ~n}" combination will always get the proper line terminating sequence for the current system.
\par \pard\plain \s253\sa240\tx2880 \b\f2\cf2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Variables}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Variables}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} MacroLanguage:050}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} variable;macro}} Variables
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Variables are part of the MicroEMACS {\uldb Macro language}{\v MacroLanguage}. They can be used wherever an {\uldb argument}{\v Arguments} (number, boolean or string) is needed.
\par {\uldb Env}{\uldb ironmental variables}{\v EnvironmentalVariables} both control and report on different aspects of the editor. {\uldb User variables}{\v UserVariables} hold values which may be changed and inspected. {\uldb Buffer variables}{\v 
BufferVariables} allow lines from {\ul buffers}{\v Buffer} to be used as values. {\uldb Interactive variables}{\v InteractiveVariables} allow macros to prompt the user for information.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Buffer Variables}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} BufferVariables}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Variables:buffervariables}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} buffer;variable}} Buffer Variables
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Buffer {\uldb variables}{\v Variables} are a way to take a line of text from a buffer and place it in a variable. They can only be queried and
 cannot be set. A buffer variable consists of the buffer name, preceded by a pound sign "#". Its value is the text between the point and the end of the line. Each use of a buffer variable advances the point to the beginning of the following line.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 For example, if you have a buffer by the name of RIGEL2, and it contains the text (the point being on the "B" of "Bloomington"): 
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 Richmond
\par Lafayette
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 {\b B}loomington
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 Indianapolis
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 Gary
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 and within a command you reference #rigel2, like in:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 insert-string #rigel2
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Mi
croEMACS would start at the current point in the RIGEL2 buffer and grab all the text up to the end of that line and pass that back. Then it would advance the point to the beginning of the next line. Thus, after the insert-string command executes, the stri
ng "Bloomington" gets inserted into the current buffer, and the buffer RIGEL2 now looks like this (the point is on the "I" of "Indianapolis"):
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 Richmond
\par Lafayette
\par Bloomington
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 {\b I}ndianapolis
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 Gary
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 When the end of a buffer variable is reached, the value returned is: {\f27\fs18 <END>}
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Environmental Variables}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} {\f10 EnvironmentalVariables}}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Variables:{\f10 environmentalvariables}}} {\plain 
\f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} variable}} Environmental Variables
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 These {\uldb variables}{\v Variables}
 are used to change or get information about various aspects of the editor. They return a current setting if used as part of an expression. All environmental variable names begin with a dollar sign "$" and are in lower case:
\par \pard\plain \s7\fi-1440\li1800\tx1800 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\uldb $acount}{\v _acount}\tab Countdown until next auto-save
\par {\uldb $asave}{\v _asave}\tab Auto-save frequency
\par {\uldb $bufhook}{\v _bufhook}\tab Command/macro run when entering a buffer
\par {\uldb $cbflags}{\v _cbflags}\tab Buffer attribute flags.
\par {\uldb $cbufname}{\v _cbufname}\tab Buffer name
\par {\uldb $cfname}{\v _cfname}\tab File name
\par {\uldb $cmdhook}{\v _cmdhook}\tab Command/macro run before each keystroke
\par {\uldb $cmode}{\v _cmode}\tab Buffer modes
\par {\uldb $curchar}{\v _curchar}\tab ASCII value of character
\par {\uldb $curcol}{\v _curcol}\tab Current column
\par {\uldb $curline}{\v _curline}\tab Current line
\par {\uldb $curwidth}{\v _curwidth}\tab Number of columns
\par {\uldb $curwind}{\v _curwind}\tab Window index
\par {\uldb $cwline}{\v _cwline}\tab Line number in current window
