\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $cmode and $gmode variables}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} _cmode}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:cmode}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K}
 $cmode;$gmode;mode}} $cmode{\plain \f2\fs20\lang1033  and }$gmode
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 The two {\uldb variables}{\v Variables} $cmode and $gmode contain a number that corresponds to the {\uldb modes}{\v ModesOfOperation} for the current {\ul buffer}{\v Buffer}
 ($cmode) and the new buffers ($gmode). They are encoded as the sum of the following numbers for each of the possible modes:
\par \pard\plain \s13\fi-2520\li2880\tqr\tx1800\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\uldb WRAP}{\v WRAP}\tab 1\tab Word wrap
\par {\uldb CMODE}{\v CMODE}\tab 2\tab C indentation and fence matching
\par \pard \s13\fi-2520\li2880\tqr\tx1800\tx2880 {\b SPELL}\tab 4\tab Interactive spell checking (Not implemented yet)
\par \pard \s13\fi-2520\li2880\tqr\tx1800\tx2880 {\uldb EXACT}{\v EXACT}\tab 8\tab Exact matching for searches
\par {\uldb VIEW}{\v VIEW}\tab 16\tab Read-only buffer
\par {\uldb OVER}{\v OVER}\tab 32\tab Overwrite mode
\par {\uldb MAGIC}{\v MAGIC}\tab 64\tab Regular expressions in search
\par {\uldb CRYPT}{\v CRYPT}\tab 128\tab Encryption mode active
\par \pard \s13\fi-2520\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx1800\tx2880 {\uldb ASAVE}{\v ASAVE}\tab 256\tab Auto-save mode
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Thus, if you wished to set the current buffer to have CMODE, EXACT, and MAGIC on, and all the others off, you would add up the values for those three, CMODE 2 + EXACT 8 + MAGIC 64 = 74, and use a statement like:

\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 set  $cmode  74
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 or, use the binary or operator to combine the different modes:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 set  $cmode  &bor  &bor  2  8  64
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Alternatively, you can also modify the modes one by one, using the {\uldb add-mode}{\v add_mode} and {\uldb add-global-mode}{\v add_global_mode} or {\uldb delete-mode}{\v delete_mode} and {\uldb delete-global-mode}{
\v delete_global_mode} commands
