\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the line position being displayed in the first column of the current window.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $fillcol variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _fillcol}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:fillcol}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $fillcol;fill}} $fillcol

\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the current fill column. It is used by the {\uldb fill-paragraph}{\v fill_paragraph} command. It can be set through the {\uldb set}{\v set} command or by using the {
\uldb set-fill-column}{\v set_fill_column} command.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: 72
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $flicker variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _flicker}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:flicker}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $flicker;grinder;hourglass
}} $flicker
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 In the MS-DOS version of MicroEMACS, this {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains a flicker flag that should be set to TRUE if the display is an IBM CGA and set to FALSE for most others.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 
In the MS-Windows version of MicroEMACS, this variable can be set to FALSE to allow an animated grinder to be displayed in place of the hourglass mouse cursor. Since this animation results, on many video displays, in an annoying flicker of the cursor, it 
is disabled when $flicker is set to TRUE.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: TRUE
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $fmtlead variable}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 
#} _fmtlead}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:fmtlead}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $fmtlead;paragraph}} $fmtlead
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 A line starting with one of the characters in the $fmtlead {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} is considered to be a text formatter command. Therefore, the following line is considered to be the start of a {\uldb 
paragraph}{\v Paragraphs}. 
\par If you are editing text destined for use by a text formatter, set $fmtlead to the command character for that formatter. That will prevent MicroEMACS from formatting what should be lines of commands meant for the formatter. If, for example, you are editing
 SCRIBE source, use the {\uldb set}{\v set} ({\ul ^XA}{\v Keystroke}) command to set $fmtlead to "{\b @}".
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: empty string
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $gflags variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _gflags}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:gflags}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $gflags}} $gflags
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Some of the ways MicroEMACS controls its internal functions can be modified by the value in the $gflags {\uldb variable}{\v Variables}. Each bit in this variable will be used to control a different function:
\par \pard\plain \s7\fi-1080\li1440\sa120\tx1440\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 1\tab If this bit is set to zero, EMACS will not automatically switch to the buffer of the first file after executing the startup macros.
\par 2\tab If this bit is set to one, suppress redraw events.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $hardtab variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _hardtab}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:hardtab}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $hardtab}} $hardtab
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the number of spaces between hard tab stops. This can be used to change the way tabs are displayed within the editor.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: 8
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 \page ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $hilight variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _hilight}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:hilight}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $hilight}} $hilight
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 When this {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains a value {\i n} between 0 and 14, it indicates that the text located between the {\ul marks}{\v mark} {\i n} and {\i n}
+1 should be highlighted. A value of 255 indicates that no highlighting is performed.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: 10
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $hjump variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _hjump}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:hjump}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $hjump}} $hjump
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the number of columns the editor should scroll the screen horizontally when a horizontal scroll is required.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: 1
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $hscroll variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _hscroll}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:hscroll}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $hscroll}} $hscroll
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} is a flag that d
etermines if MicroEMACS will scroll the entire window horizontally, or just the current line. The default value, TRUE, results in the entire window being shifted left or right when the cursor goes off the edge of the screen.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $hscrlbar variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _hscrlbar}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:hscrlbar}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $hscrlbar;scroll bar}}
 $hscrlbar
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This boolean {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} exists only under the MS-Windows version of MicroEMACS. If it is TRUE, an horizontal scroll bar is available at the bottom of each {\ul screen}{\v Screen}
, allowing you to scroll the text in the current {\ul window}{\v Window} right and left.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 If $hscrlbar is FALSE, the horizontal scroll bar is not present.
\par Default value: TRUE
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $isterm variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _isterm}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:isterm}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $isterm;incremental search}}
 $isterm
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the character used to terminate incremental search string inputs.
\par Default value: the last key bound to {\uldb meta-prefix}{\v meta_prefix} (initially: Escape character)
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $kill variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 
#} _kill}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:kill}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $kill}} $kill
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the first 127 characters currently in the {\ul kill buffer}{\v KillBuffer}.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Attempts to set this variable are ignored.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $language variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _language}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:language}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $language}} $language

\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the name of the nati
onal language in which MicroEMACS messages will be displayed. (Currently MicroEMACS is available in English, French, Spanish, Latin, Portuguese, Dutch, German, and Pig Latin).
\par \pard \s6\sa120 The MS-Windows version of MicroEMACS is currently available in English only.
\par Attempts to set this variable are ignored. Changing the language used by MicroEMACS requires recompiling.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $lastkey variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _lastkey}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:lastkey}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $lastkey}} $lastkey
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains a number representing the ASCII value of the last key press processed by MicroEMACS. This variable 
does not contain any indication that the last keystroke was prefixed by the {\ul Meta}{\v MetaKey} or the {\b Alt} keys. Further more, function or special keys are perceived as the last character of their {\ul keystroke representation}{\v Keystroke}.

\par Note that this variable does not change during playback of a {\ul keyboard macro}{\v KeyboardMacro}.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Setting this variable does not have any effect on the editor beyond changing the variable's value.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $lastmesg variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _lastmesg}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:lastmesg}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $lastmesg}} $lastmesg

\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the text of the last message which MicroEMACS wrote on the {\ul message line}{\v MessageLine}.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Setting this variable does not have any effect on the editor beyond changing the variable's value.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $line variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 
#} _line}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:line}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $line}} $line
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the first 127 characters of the current line. Setting this variable overwrites the contents of the current line.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $lterm variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _lterm}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:lterm}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $lterm}} $lterm
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the string of characters to use as a line terminator when writing a file to disk. By default, it is an empty string, which causes a newline to be written (under
 MS-DOS or MS-Windows, this translates into a carriage return character followed by a line feed character).
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Under some operating systems, the value of this variable is irrelevant.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $lwidth variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _lwidth}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:lwidth}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $lwidth}} $lwidth
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the number of characters of the current line.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Attempts to set this variable are ignored.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $match variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _match}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:match}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $match}} $match
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the last string matched by a {\uldb search}{\v SearchingAndReplacing} operation.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Attempts to set this variable are ignored.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 \page ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $mmove variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _mmove}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:mmove}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $mmove;mouse}} $mmove
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 If this {\uldb va}{\uldb riable}{\v Variables} it is equal to 2, any mouse movement results in a mouse action ({\ul MSm}{\v MouseAction}, {\ul S-MSm}{\v MouseAction} or {\ul MS^m}{\v MouseAction}).
\par If this variable is set to 1, some mouse movement that are of marginal interest (like while a {\ul popup buffer}{\v PopupBuffer} is being displayed or, under MS-Windows, while no mouse button is pressed) are ignored.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 If $mmove is set to 0, all mouse movements are ignored.
\par Default value: 1
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $modeflag variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
