\fs16\up6 #} _softtab}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:softtab}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $softtab}} $softtab
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 The value of this {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} relates to the number of spaces inserted by MicroEMACS when the {\uldb handle-tab}{\v handle_tab} command (which is normally bound to the TAB key) is invoked:
\par \pard\plain \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab If $softtab is {\i n}, strictly positive, tabs stops are located at every {\i n}{\fs16\up6 th} column and the handle-tab command inserts {\ul space charac}{\ul 
ters}{\b  }in sufficient number to move the {\ul point}{\v Point} to the next tab stop.
\par \pard \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 \tab If $softtab is zero, the handle-tab command inserts {\ul true tab characters}.{\b  }
\par \tab If $softtab is strictly negative, the handle-tab command fails.
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This variable can be set by passing a {\ul numeric argument}{\v Argument} to handle-tab or by directly using the {\uldb set}{\v set} command.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: 0
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $sres variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 
#} _sres}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:sres}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $sres}} $sres
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains a string that identifies the current screen resolution (CGA, MONO, EGA or VGA on the IBM-PC, LOW, MEDIUM, HIGH or
 DENSE on the Atari ST1040, MSWIN under Microsoft Windows and NORMAL on most others).
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Depending on the hardware and operating system MicroEMACS is running on, setting this variable may allow you to change the screen resolution. Not that under MS-Windows, attempts to set this variable are ignored.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $ssave variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _ssave}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:ssave}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $ssave}} $ssave
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 If this boolean {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} is TRUE, MicroEMACS perform "safe saves": when it is asked to save the current buffer to disk, it writes it out to a temporary file, deletes the original file, a
nd then renames the temporary to the old file name.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 
If $ssave is FALSE, MicroEMACS performs saves by directly overwriting the original file, thus risking loss of data if a system crash occurs before the end of the save operation. On the other hand, this mode insures that the original file attributes (owner
ship and access rights) are preserved on systems that support these (like UNIX).
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: TRUE.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $sscroll variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _sscroll}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:sscroll}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $sscroll}} $sscroll
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 If this boolean {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} is TRUE, MicroEMACS is configured for smooth vertical scrolling: when the cursor moves off the top or bottom of the current {\ul window}{\v Window}
, the window's contents scroll up or down one line at a time.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 If $sscroll is FALSE, scrolling occurs by half pages.
\par Default value: FALSE
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $status variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _status}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:status}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $status}} $status
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This boolean {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the status returned by the last command. This is usually used with the {\uldb !FORCE}{\v .FORCE}
 directive to check on the success of a search, or a file operation.
\par Setting this variable can be used to return a FALSE status from a {\ul macro}{\v M}{\v acro}.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $sterm variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _sterm}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:sterm}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $sterm;replace;search}} $sterm

\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the character used to terminate search string inputs.
\par Default value: the last key bound to {\uldb meta-prefix}{\v meta_prefix} (initially: Escape character)
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $target variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _target}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:target}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $target}} $target
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the column position where the {\ul point}{\v Point} will attempt to move after a {\uldb next-line}{\v next_line} or {\uldb previous-line}{\v previous_line}
 command. Unless the previous command was next-line or previous-line, the default value for this variable is the current column.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $time variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 
#} _time}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:time}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $time}} $time
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains a string corresponding to the current date and time. Usually this is given in a form like to "Mon May 09 10:10:58 1988". Not all operating systems support this.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $timeflag variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _timeflag}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:timeflag}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $timeflag}} $timeflag

\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 If this boolean {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} is TRUE, the current time is displayed on the bottom {\ul mode line}{\v ModeLine} of each {\ul screen}{\v Screen}.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Default value: FALSE.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Note: Under MS-Windows, this feature currently does not operate properly because MicroEMACS makes incorrect assumptions about the format of the time string (see {\uldb $time}{\v _time}).
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $tpause variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _tpause}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:tpause}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $tpause}} $tpause
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the length of the pause used to show a matched fence when the current buffer is in CMODE and a closing fence ( a character among "{\b )\}]}") has been typed.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 On most systems, this pause is performed by a CPU loop and therefore, the value of $tpause may need to be adjusted to compensate for the processor's speed.
\par Under MS-Windows, the pause is performed by a bona-fide timer and $tpause is expressed in milliseconds. The default value is 1000.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $version variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _version}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:version}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $version}} $version
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the current MicroEMACS version number (i.e. "{\f9 3.11c}").
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Attempts to set this variable are ignored.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $vscrlbar variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _vscrlbar}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:vscrlbar}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $vscrlbar;scroll bar}}
 $vscrlbar
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This boolean {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} exists only under the MS-Windows version of MicroEMACS. If it is TRUE, a vertical scroll bar is available at the right end of each {\ul screen}{\v Screen}
, allowing you to scroll the text in the current {\ul window}{\v Window} up and down.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 If $vscrlbar is FALSE, the vertical scroll bar is not present.
\par Default value: TRUE
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $wchars variable}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} _wchars}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:wchars}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $wchars;word}} $wchars
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} is used to define what a {\uldb word}{\v Words} is for MicroEMACS. It contains the list of all the characters that can be considered part of a word.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 If $wchar is empty, a word is defined as composed of upper and lower case letters, numerals (0 to 9) and the underscore character.
\par Default value: empty
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $wline variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _wline}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:wline}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $wline}} $wline
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the number of lines displayed in the current {\ul window}{\v Window}, excluding the {\ul mode line}{\v ModeLine}.
\par Setting this variable is equivalent to using the {\uldb resize-window}{\v resize_window} command with a {\ul numeric argument}{\v Argument}.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $wraphook variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _wraphook}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:wraphook}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $wraphook;hook;wrap}}
 $wraphook
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the name of a {\ul command}{\v Command} or {\ul macro}{\v Macro} which is executed when a {\ul buffer}{\v Buffer} is in {\uldb WRAP}{\v WRAP}
 mode and it is time to wrap the current line.
\par Default value: {\uldb wrap-word}{\v wrap_word}
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $writehook variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _writehook}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:writehook}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $writehook;hook;write}
} $writehook
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the name of a {\ul command}{\v Command} or {\ul macro}{\v Macro} which is invoked whenever MicroEMACS attempts to write a file out to disk. This is executed before th
e file is written, allowing you to process a file on the way out.
\par Default value: {\uldb nop}{\v nop}
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $xpos variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 
#} _xpos}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:xpos}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $xpos;mouse}} $xpos
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the horizontal {\ul screen}{\v Screen} coordinate where the mouse was located the last time a {\uldb mouse button}{\v MouseCommands} was pressed or released.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 The leftmost column is considered to be 0 in screen coordinates.
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $yankflag variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} _yankflag}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:yankflag}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $yankflag}} $yankflag

\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This boolean {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} controls the placement of the {\ul point}{\v Point} after a {\uldb yank}{\v yank}, {\uldb yank-pop}{\v yank_pop}, {\uldb insert-file}{\v insert_file} or {\uldb insert-clip
}{\v insert_c}{\v lip} command.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 If $yankflag is FALSE, the point is moved to the end of the yanked or inserted text.
\par If $yankflag is TRUE, the cursor remains at the start of the yanked or inserted text.
\par Default value: FALSE
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} $ypos variable}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 
#} _ypos}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} EVariables:ypos}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} $ypos;mouse}} $ypos
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb variable}{\v Variables} contains the vertical {\ul screen}{\v Screen} coordinate where the mouse was located the last time a {\uldb mouse button}{\v MouseCommands} was pressed or released.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 The top row is considered to be 0 in screen coordinates.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Interactive Variables}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} InteractiveVariables}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Variables:interactivevariables}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote 
\pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} interactive;variable}} Interactive Variables
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Interactive {\uldb variables}{\v Variables} are actually a method to prompt the user for a string. This is done by using an at sign "@" followed with a string {\uldb argument}{\v Arguments}
. The string is displayed on the {\ul message line}{\v MessageLine}, and the editor waits for the user to type in a string which is then returned as the value of the interactive variable. For example:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 find-file {\b @}"What file? "
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 will ask the user for a file name, and then attempt to find it. Note also that complex expressions can be built up with these operators, such as: 
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 set %default "file1"
\par \pard \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 {\b @}&cat &cat "File to decode[" %default "]: "
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 which prompts the user with the string:
\par \pard\plain \s4\fi-2160\li2880\sa120\tx2880 \f27\fs18\lang1033 File to decode[file1]:
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} User Variables}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} UserVariables}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Variables:uservariables}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} variable}} User Variables
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 User {\uldb variables}{\v Variables}
 allow you to store strings and manipulate them. These strings can be pieces of text, numbers (in text form), or the logical values TRUE and FALSE. These variables can be combined, tested, inserted into buffers, and otherwise used to control the way your 
{\uldb macros}{\v MacroLanguage} execute. Up to 512 user variables may be in use in one editing session. All user variable names must begin with a percent sign "{\b %}
" and may contain any printing character. Only the first 10 characters are significant (i.e. differences beyond the tenth character are ignored).
\par \pard \s6\sa120 When a user variable has not been set, it has the value: "ERROR".
